  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What is achilles tendonitis?",
  "response": "Achilles tendonitis is an overuse injury characterized by inflammation of the Achilles tendon, the thick band of tissue connecting the calf muscles to the heel bone. It commonly arises from repetitive stress, sudden increases in activity, or tight calf muscles, and is prevalent among athletes and active individuals.\n\n**Key Features:**\n- **Causes**: Overuse (e.g., running, jumping), abrupt activity changes, poor footwear, or biomechanical issues (flat feet, tight calves).\n- **Symptoms**: Pain/stiffness near the heel (worse in the morning or after activity), swelling, tenderness, and possible warmth over the tendon.\n- **Types**:\n  - **Non-insertional**: Affects the mid-portion of the tendon.\n  - **Insertional**: Occurs where the tendon attaches to the heel bone, sometimes involving bone spurs.\n- **Risk Factors**: Age (30\u201350 years), sports participation, obesity, certain medications (e.g., corticosteroids, fluoroquinolones), and anatomical factors.\n\n**Diagnosis**: Clinical evaluation (physical exam, history) and imaging (ultrasound/MRI) to assess severity and exclude tears.\n\n**Treatment**:\n- **Acute Phase**: Rest, ice, NSAIDs, and activity modification.\n- **Rehabilitation**: Eccentric strengthening exercises, stretching, and physical therapy.\n- **Adjunct Therapies**: Orthotics, night splints, or shockwave therapy.\n- **Surgery**: Rare, reserved for chronic cases unresponsive to conservative care.\n\n**Prevention**: Gradual training progression, proper footwear, calf stretches, and cross-training to avoid overuse.\n\n**Complications**: Chronic degeneration (tendinosis) or tendon rupture if untreated.\n\nEarly intervention is crucial to prevent progression and ensure recovery.",
